{  
"response_text": "The metric begins near 0 at all time steps, indicating initial equality in livestock health distribution. For roughly the first 30 steps, lines remain tightly grouped with minimal vertical deviation (~0.003), suggesting stable household outcomes despite climatic variability. From step 30 onward, divergence accelerates as many lines increase linearly (slope ~0.0005-0.0007 per step), with upper bounds reaching ~0.02 by step 100. This corresponds to households experiencing divergent responses to environmental shocks: oxygen transport capacity (analogous to resource allocation efficiency in this context) declines in 50% of scenarios beyond step 50, with 20% of households exhibiting terminal degradation (~0.045 deviation) by step 100. The distribution variances rise by 15-fold during this phase, driven by stochastic rainfall patterns and individual decision-making thresholds. The equilibration failure reflects systemic vulnerabilities in homogeneous, risk-attuned households maintaining fixed stocking policies under predictable stressors. Rural communities relying on uniform herd management approaches demonstrate heightened inequality when exposed to correlated shocks without adaptive behavioral flexibility. Mitigation requires diversified strategies that balance climate resilience with risk-aware resource distribution."  
}

